revisions.rev:
'''Feminist Digital Humanities''' is a more recent development in the field of [[Digital Humanities]] as a whole. Feminist Digital Humanities has risen partly due to recent criticism of the propensity of Digital Humanities to further patriarchal or hegemonic discourses in the Academy.<ref>{{cite book| publisher= U of Minnesota P| editor= Matthew K. Gold |last=Liu|first=Alan|chapter=Where is Cultural Criticism in the Digital Humanities?|title= Debates in the Digital Humanities|location= Minneapolis | year= 2012|url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/30}}</ref> Some of the research in feminist digital humanities centres on the exclusion of women from histories of technology<ref>{{cite article| last=Chun|first=Wendy|title=On Software, or the Persistence of Visible Knowledge| journal= Grey Room| year= 2004}}</ref> and the use of technology to promote feminist scholarship.
Scholars Wendy Chun and [[Katherine Hayles|N. Katherine Hayles]] could be considered feminist digital humanities scholars.
